      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2668367924" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13326083165356917663">*listened to audio book*<br/><br/>So, I listened to this book twice. As soon as I finished the first reading I at once started it over. Because the first time every word went in one ear and out the other and not one word remained inside my head. Why? Because the writing style is so beautiful you must concentrate to understand it, but I was busy doing so many things while listening that often my thoughts drifted to places other than the audio book. <br/><br/>But the stories were WONDERFUL. Father Brown is such a fun</span>
  <span id="freeText13326083165356917663" style="display:none">*listened to audio book*<br /><br />So, I listened to this book twice. As soon as I finished the first reading I at once started it over. Because the first time every word went in one ear and out the other and not one word remained inside my head. Why? Because the writing style is so beautiful you must concentrate to understand it, but I was busy doing so many things while listening that often my thoughts drifted to places other than the audio book. <br /><br />But the stories were WONDERFUL. Father Brown is such a funny, witty little priest. Each story is such a unique mystery. And there was always some sort of theology or message to be learned. And the description was both beautiful and necessary for the plot - every word of each story definitely counted (that's why you can't listen and drift away for a moment and expect to still have all of the story).<br /><br />I saw that a few reviewers said there was racism in the book. These stories were written a hundred years ago, so they are certainly not "politically correct" but neither are they racist. <br /><br />When one person was talking of black people and made the comment, "Sometimes I'm not surprised that they lynch them." <br /><br />And Father Brown said, "I'm never surprised at sin." <br /><br />So, yeah, they spoke freely of black people as black people, and some villains were black (there were plenty of white villains too). But the book nor the author was racist, but made out as if all humans are humans and can be saved by God. <br /><br />The book was overall clean, considering that some of them are murder mysteries ;) But nothing graphic, no language, no sensuality. <br /><br />Oooh. . . and I REALLY love the last story in the book. It's just so . . . whimsical?</span>
  <a data-text-id="13326083165356917663" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


